Research Interests

I am interested in elections, parties, and womens representation and political participation in non-democratic political regimes.

Questions I hope to answer

What is the role of type of electoral system and form of governance is the success of hegemonic parties in electoral authoritarian regimes? Is womens political participation related to the Number of Effective Parliamentary Parties? Are women more or less likely to succeed in regimes with a hegemonic party?

Methods

I am interested in various regression models, particularly in panel data, cluster analysis, technics applied in natural experiments, text analysis, and qualitative methods such as interviews and focus groups.

Relevant data

  • The Authoritarian Regimes Dataset (ARD) is a comprehensive dataset on authoritarian regimes in the world between 1972-2014. It distinguishes different forms of authoritarian regimes by their institutional setups. (data)
  • The Database of Political Institutions (DPI) presents institutional and electoral results data such as measures of checks and balances, tenure and stability of the government, identification of party affiliation and ideology, and fragmentation of opposition and government parties in the legislature. (data)
  • V-Dem database is data with over 350 indicators on democratic and authoritarian systems across the world from 1900 to the present (data)

Descriptive statistics of three measurements of the ENP.

Fig 1: Density Plots for Effective Number of Parties.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
require(gridExtra)

density1 <- parties %>% 
      ggplot() + 
      aes(x = enp_lt) +
      geom_density() + 
      labs(x = "ENP by Laakso and Taagepera (1979)")
density2 <- parties %>% 
      ggplot() + 
        aes(x = enp_mol) +
      geom_density() + 
      labs(x = "ENP by Molinar (1991)")
density3 <- parties %>% 
      ggplot() + 
      aes(x = enp_gol) +
      geom_density() + 
      labs(x = "ENP by Golosov (2010)")
grid.arrange(density1, density2, density3, ncol=3,
             top = (""))

Fig 2: Scatter Plots for Effective Number of Parties.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
require(gridExtra)

scatter1 <- parties %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  aes(x = year, y = enp_lt) + 
  geom_point(alpha = .2) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "ENP by Laakso and Taagepera (1979)")
scatter2 <- parties %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  aes(x = year, y = enp_mol) + 
  geom_point(alpha = .2) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "ENP by Molinar (1991)")
scatter3 <-  parties %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  aes(x = year, y = enp_gol) + 
  geom_point(alpha = .2) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "ENP by Golosov (2010)")
grid.arrange(scatter1, scatter2, scatter3, ncol=3,
             top = (""))

Fig 3: Scatter plot and boxplots of ENP by Laakso and Taagepera by type of electoral system.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

parties %>%
  mutate(elecsys = ifelse(elecsys==1,'Proportional Representation',elecsys)) %>%
  mutate(elecsys = ifelse(elecsys==0,'Mixed Electoral System',elecsys)) %>%
  mutate(elecsys = ifelse(elecsys==2,'Plurality',elecsys)) %>%
  filter(elecsys!=".") %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  aes(x = elecsys, y = enp_lt, colour=elecsys)+
  geom_boxplot(colour="black")+
  geom_jitter(height = 0, alpha = .5)+
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07"))+
  labs(x= "", y = "ENP by Laasko and Taagapera", colour = "Electoral systems")+
  ggtitle("")
